# Sync Sphere

Sync Sphere is a lightweight smart-home / IoT control platform (backend + frontend) that uses MQTT for device communication and a modern React + Tailwind frontend for device management and control.

Features

- User authentication (signup / login)
- Device registration and management
- Channel creation and control (toggle channel state)
- Device configuration endpoint for devices to fetch their runtime config
- MQTT integration for sending commands to devices

Tech stack

- Backend: Node.js, Express, Mongoose, MQTT
- Frontend: React, Vite, Tailwind CSS, Axios, Zustand

Quick links

- Backend entry: [backend/src/server.js](backend/src/server.js#L1)
- Frontend entry: [frontend/src/main.jsx](frontend/src/main.jsx#L1)

Prerequisites

- Node.js >= 18
- npm or yarn
- MongoDB instance (local or cloud)
- MQTT broker (supports TLS in current config)

Environment variables

Backend (.env)

- `MONGO_URI` - MongoDB connection string
- `JWT_SECRET` - JWT signing secret
- `PORT` - Backend port (default 5000)
- `MQTT_HOST` - MQTT broker host
- `MQTT_PORT` - MQTT broker port
- `MQTT_USERNAME` - MQTT username (optional)
- `MQTT_PASSWORD` - MQTT password (optional)

Frontend (.env)

- `VITE_API_URL` - Backend API base URL (default `http://localhost:5000/api`)

Install & run

Backend

1. Install dependencies

```
cd backend
npm install
```

2. Create a `.env` with the variables above, then start in development:

```
npm run dev
```

Frontend

1. Install dependencies

```
cd frontend
npm install
```

2. Start the dev server

```
npm run dev
```

API Reference

Base path: `/api`

Authentication

- POST `/api/auth/signup` — Register new user
	- body: `{ name, email, password }`
	- response: `{ token, user }`
- POST `/api/auth/login` — Login
	- body: `{ email, password }`
	- response: `{ token, user }`

Devices (protected)

- POST `/api/devices` — Register a device
	- body: `{ deviceId, name }`
- GET `/api/devices` — List devices for authenticated user
- DELETE `/api/devices/:deviceId` — Remove a device

Channels (protected)

- POST `/api/channels/:deviceId` — Create a channel for a device
	- body: `{ channelId, name, gpio, type, room }`
- GET `/api/channels/:deviceId` — Get channels for a device
- PUT `/api/channels/toggle/:channelId` — Toggle channel state (publishes MQTT command)

Device config (public for devices)

- GET `/api/device-config/:deviceId` — Device fetches its configuration (channels, online state)

MQTT topic format

When toggling a channel the backend publishes to a topic of the form:

```
syncsphere/device/{deviceId}/channel/{channelId}/command
```

Code structure (high level)

- backend/
	- `src/server.js` — Express app & route mounting
	- `src/config` — `db.js`, `mqtt.js`
	- `src/routes` — Express route files (`authRoutes.js`, `deviceRoutes.js`, ...)
	- `src/controllers` — Route handlers
	- `src/models` — Mongoose models (`User`, `Device`, `Channel`)
	- `src/mqtt` — `publisher.js`, `subscriber.js` helpers

- frontend/
	- `src/api` — Axios client and API wrappers
	- `src/pages` — `Login`, `Register`, `Dashboard`, `Home`
	- `src/components` — Layout and UI components
	- `src/store` — Zustand stores (auth, theme)

Testing & development notes

- The backend expects JWT tokens in `Authorization: Bearer <token>` headers (frontend sets this via axios interceptors).
- MQTT client is configured to use `mqtts` protocol by default. Adjust `src/config/mqtt.js` if your broker uses non-TLS or different connection options.

Next steps / Suggestions

- Add validation and request schemas (e.g., using `joi` or `express-validator`).
- Add unit / integration tests for critical controllers.
- Improve frontend UI (components are scaffolded in `frontend/src/components`).

